blog.description:
My fandom name is Beachy, and this is a multi-fandom blog. 
I'm also a multi-shipper. It's likely I do not sail your ship, but I don't wank and expect visitors to play nicely as well. That includes not adding hate or negativity to my posts, altering them to suit your own ships, or removing my original comments. If you do, you will be blocked.
IRL they call me Doctor. Yep, I'm that old. Sometimes I write things that other people watch. It's all good! I like mocha latte with bourbon. A lot.

summary: Voyage of the Damned - Behind the Scenes (Part 11)  Excerpts from Doctor Who Magazine #390 & 391′s “You Ask David” articles by...
caption:
Voyage of the Damned - Behind the Scenes (Part 11)

Excerpts from Doctor Who Magazine #390 & 391′s “You Ask David” articles by Benjamin Cook

Angela Prout asks: You’re frequently pictured in public wearing an open collar and very, very tight jeans. I’m not complaining! Are you secretly a bit of a tart, or are you teasing the fans?

David Tennant: I’m not aware of being a tart. I’m rather shocked and bemused that Angela should think such a thing. Teasing them with what?

DWM: Trousers, collars, that sort of thing.

David Tennant: I’m just trying to get by. If I am a tart, which I would refute strongly, it’s by accident.

Sue Heal asks: Do you realise how sexy you are in the brown pinstripe suit - especially how tight it is around the bum, which really sets female fans’ pulses racing?

David Tennant: Sexy in the pinstripe? Well, I have nothing to say about my bum. Anything I say will condemn me to… well, believe me. I didn’t… there was no… oh, I don’t know what to say.

DWM: It’s not intentional then? You’ve never asked [costume designer] Louise Page to tighten the backs of your trousers?

David Tennant: Of course not, no. [Laughs]. What’s with these questions, ladies?

Emma Wheatley asks: Bit of a cheeky one, but we need to know, are you a true Scotsman (ie what’s under your kilt)?

David Tennant: I have been on occasions, yes. It took me a while before I was brave enough.

DWM: You wore a kilt to last year’s BAFTA ceremony, didn’t you?

David Tennant: Yes, and I wasn’t wearing any pants!

Other parts of this set: [one]  [two]  [three]  [four]  [five]  [six]  [seven]  [eight]  [nine]  [ten]
[All of my Tenth Doctor Behind-the-Scenes sets ]

body:
Much Ado About Nothing

David Tennant and Catherine Tate

Omg guys. I just finished it and I have a few things to say.

  • It was freaking funny as heck
  • I mean really
  • David and Catherine are THE comedic duo
  • On that note, it was weird seeing them as love interests, at first—after seeing them play platonic bffs—
  • But ngl I loved it
  • They are such a great pair
  • I’ve missed watching Catherine
  • She’s so funny
  • And a great actress
  • And David Tennant was f i n e
  • Like WOW
  • Yes in everything. Even that…costume
  • I love you, sir.
  • Again, David and Catherine…just
  • Yes
  • Can I get that again???
  • I’m going to watch this again very soon

tags: here we are! hello! thank you for sending Many Memes even though i never answer them
summary: “I don’t expect anyone else to understand.” (From Sophia? Also, hello!)
question: “I don’t expect anyone else to understand.” (From Sophia? Also, hello!)
answer:
sentence meme (accepting)

“Try me.” There were many, many things in the Doctor’s life, especially things concerning humans, that people did not expect him to understand. Usually, he was the only one able to make sense of them - so he said, try me, as he entered the room, and the little huddle of concerned staff (what do they do in a situation like this one?!) turned to look at him, but the Doctor wasn’t stopping. He had come for supplies. “Alien-type creature come crawling around the ceilings of your … what is this, is it a hospital?” he did pause to frown around the room, for an instant, just to check - like the interior of one room might tell him where he was. 

“Believe me,” he told the young woman - “I’d understand that.” 

The Doctor crouched, so that he could flash the sonic in the direction of the tiny bar-fridge. It buzzed - the fridge’s lock clicked undone - one of the small number of staff there rushed forward to stop him getting his fingers in the MEDICAL SUPPLIES - AUTHORISED ACCESS ONLY, but the Doctor was collecting vials and medicines, and he held up the psychic paper, other hand still working to stow the medicines away. “I’ll tell you what I think,” he announced, though, and he was standing up again - many of the supplies were left behind - all he knew about this creature was that it was fast, it was hungry, and it got very, very cranky in between mealtimes. “I think we’d better feed it. Have any other plastics? Come on!” it was a shame, these new-fangled hospitals - big strides in anti-pollution laws but single-use plastics were going out of fashion, it was hard to find anything this guy could eat, these days. Plastic syringes were the only sure bet he’d had. 

The Doctor stood up again, and he was already headed for the door.

caption:
The Definitive Good Omens Special Editions Now Available For Pre-Order 

The beloved cult novdavidel Good Omens by Sir Terry Pratchett and Neil Gaiman will be republished later this year in five different edtions featuring a corrected text and colour illustrations. The Definitive Good Omens features a new revised text, approved by Neil Gaiman and the Pratchett Estate, which clears up many typos and errors from previous versions. The new editions also feature line drawings and full colour illustrations from Paul Kidby, Terry Pratchett’s preferred artist (see above).
